name: 2-methylnaphthalene
Reason: Basic unit naphthalene has a melting point of 80.4°C. A methyl substituent generally lowers the melting point because of its electron-donating properties, which can disrupt the pi-stacking interactions present in polycyclic aromatic systems and also create a molecular asymmetry, which reduces the melting point. In the case of 2-methylnaphthalene, adding a methyl group to naphthalene would reduce the melting point by approximately 46.7°C (80.4°C - 33.7°C).
